{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MMeAwRNnVoeJ111SfCPd8J","type":"tool_result","content":"   458→## GEPA: Fitness Evaluation and Pareto Front\n   459→\n   460→The Guided Evolutionary Prompt Adaptation (GEPA) subsystem extends the evolution\n   461→pipeline with multi-objective fitness evaluation for population-based prompt\n   462→evolution. It lives in `internal/evolution/fitness.go`.\n   463→\n   464→### Fitness Records\n   465→\n   466→Each completed run is evaluated into a `FitnessRecord` containing:\n   467→- **RunID / WorkflowName / Candidate** — identifies the run and its candidate\n   468→  (e.g. a prompt version)\n   469→- **Success** — whether the run reached `succeeded` state\n   470→- **RetryCount** — number of step re-executions (detected by counting duplicate\n   471→  step names in execution history)\n   472→- **Duration** — wall-clock time from start to completion\n   473→\n   474→Records are persisted as JSONL at `.cloche/evolution/fitness/<workflow>.jsonl`.\n   475→\n   476→### Aggregation\n   477→\n   478→`AggregateFitness` groups records by candidate and computes two objectives:\n   479→\n   480→1. **Success rate** — fraction of runs that succeeded\n   481→2. **Efficiency** — `1 / (1 + avgRetries + avgDurationMinutes)`, rewarding\n   482→   faster candidates with fewer retries\n   483→\n   484→### Pareto Front\n   485→\n   486→`ComputeParetoFront` returns the non-dominated set using standard Pareto\n   487→dominance: candidate A dominates B when A is at least as good in all objectives\n   488→and strictly better in at least one. The front represents the optimal tradeoff\n   489→between reliability and speed — no candidate on the front can be improved in one\n   490→objective without sacrificing the other.\n   491→\n   492→### Candidate Selection\n   493→\n   494→`SelectCandidate` (in `internal/evolution/selector.go`) picks a candidate for\n   495→the next evolution cycle using a stochastic strategy that balances exploitation\n   496→and exploration:\n   497→\n   498→- **70%** — pick a random candidate from the Pareto front (exploit known-good\n   499→  tradeoffs)\n   500→- **30%** — pick a random non-front candidate (explore potentially improving\n   501→  variants)\n   502→\n   503→If only one pool has candidates (e.g. all candidates are on the front, or no\n   504→front candidates exist), selection draws from whichever pool is available.\n   505→Returns nil when the candidate list is empty, signaling the caller to use the\n   506→base prompt.\n   507→\n   508→### Population Configuration\n   509→\n   510→Population-based evolution is controlled by `PopulationConfig`:\n   511→\n   512→```go\n   513→type PopulationConfig struct {\n   514→    Enabled          bool\n   515→    MaxCandidates    int\n   516→    MinRunsToPromote int\n   517→}\n   518→```\n   519→\n   520→## Future Work (Out of Scope)\n   521→\n   522→- **Step removal/mutation** — modifying or removing existing step definitions\n   523→  (higher risk, needs careful design around backwards compatibility)\n   524→- **`cloche evolve --revert <evo-id>`** — automated revert from snapshots\n   525→- **Helpfulness tracking** — automatically detecting whether applied lessons\n   526→  actually reduced failure rates, and pruning unhelpful ones\n   527→- **Cross-project learning** — sharing knowledge base insights across projects\n   528→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa9a8c88-04cf-4eb4-ae7d-479d0dedfad3","uuid":"78842bc5-53b3-4626-9918-65170731818c","timestamp":"2026-03-18T16:15:25.436Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-02-24-self-evolution-design.md","content":"## GEPA: Fitness Evaluation and Pareto Front\n\nThe Guided Evolutionary Prompt Adaptation (GEPA) subsystem extends the evolution\npipeline with multi-objective fitness evaluation for population-based prompt\nevolution. It lives in `internal/evolution/fitness.go`.\n\n### Fitness Records\n\nEach completed run is evaluated into a `FitnessRecord` containing:\n- **RunID / WorkflowName / Candidate** — identifies the run and its candidate\n  (e.g. a prompt version)\n- **Success** — whether the run reached `succeeded` state\n- **RetryCount** — number of step re-executions (detected by counting duplicate\n  step names in execution history)\n- **Duration** — wall-clock time from start to completion\n\nRecords are persisted as JSONL at `.cloche/evolution/fitness/<workflow>.jsonl`.\n\n### Aggregation\n\n`AggregateFitness` groups records by candidate and computes two objectives:\n\n1. **Success rate** — fraction of runs that succeeded\n2. **Efficiency** — `1 / (1 + avgRetries + avgDurationMinutes)`, rewarding\n   faster candidates with fewer retries\n\n### Pareto Front\n\n`ComputeParetoFront` returns the non-dominated set using standard Pareto\ndominance: candidate A dominates B when A is at least as good in all objectives\nand strictly better in at least one. The front represents the optimal tradeoff\nbetween reliability and speed — no candidate on the front can be improved in one\nobjective without sacrificing the other.\n\n### Candidate Selection\n\n`SelectCandidate` (in `internal/evolution/selector.go`) picks a candidate for\nthe next evolution cycle using a stochastic strategy that balances exploitation\nand exploration:\n\n- **70%** — pick a random candidate from the Pareto front (exploit known-good\n  tradeoffs)\n- **30%** — pick a random non-front candidate (explore potentially improving\n  variants)\n\nIf only one pool has candidates (e.g. all candidates are on the front, or no\nfront candidates exist), selection draws from whichever pool is available.\nReturns nil when the candidate list is empty, signaling the caller to use the\nbase prompt.\n\n### Population Configuration\n\nPopulation-based evolution is controlled by `PopulationConfig`:\n\n```go\ntype PopulationConfig struct {\n    Enabled          bool\n    MaxCandidates    int\n    MinRunsToPromote int\n}\n```\n\n## Future Work (Out of Scope)\n\n- **Step removal/mutation** — modifying or removing existing step definitions\n  (higher risk, needs careful design around backwards compatibility)\n- **`cloche evolve --revert <evo-id>`** — automated revert from snapshots\n- **Helpfulness tracking** — automatically detecting whether applied lessons\n  actually reduced failure rates, and pruning unhelpful ones\n- **Cross-project learning** — sharing knowledge base insights across projects\n","numLines":71,"startLine":458,"totalLines":528}}}
